WEBVTT

00:04.874 --> 00:05.222
.

00:05.266 --> 00:08.660
- You've been helping me do my
job better since you got here.

00:08.704 --> 00:09.835
- I couldn't help it.

00:09.879 --> 00:11.098
- No need to help it.

00:11.141 --> 00:13.100
- [farting]
- The fart doctor now.

00:13.143 --> 00:14.362
Punchline.

00:14.405 --> 00:15.406
- What happened today
was a result

00:15.450 --> 00:16.625
of a medical ailment, okay?

00:16.668 --> 00:19.497
- Like anyone's gonna care
about that.

00:19.541 --> 00:22.761
- Jack wants to convert Med
into a for-profit hospital.

00:22.805 --> 00:25.242
He wants to put it
to a board vote.

00:25.286 --> 00:28.680
- If Jack succeeds,
there goes Med as we know it.

00:28.724 --> 00:31.683
- I'm officially in
end-stage renal disease.

00:31.727 --> 00:33.859
- Sean would be your
best-possible donor match.

00:33.903 --> 00:35.209
- That's not an option.

00:35.252 --> 00:37.689
- Your dad,
his health is getting worse.

00:37.733 --> 00:40.431
He can't know that
you learned this from me.

00:44.696 --> 00:45.871
[rhythmic knocking]

00:45.915 --> 00:47.047
- [chuckles] Hey.

00:47.090 --> 00:50.050
[sentimental music]

00:50.093 --> 00:52.052
♪

00:52.095 --> 00:53.531
Hey!
- Hey.

00:53.575 --> 00:55.185
- What are you doing here?
- I was in the neighborhood.

00:55.229 --> 00:56.752
- Yeah?
- Thought I'd swing by.

00:56.795 --> 00:59.059
- All right. Come in.
You hungry?

00:59.102 --> 01:00.451
Got some oatmeal.

01:00.495 --> 01:03.889
- Oh, no, I'm good. Thanks.

01:03.933 --> 01:05.935
- Got your scrubs on.

01:05.978 --> 01:07.719
Going to work?

01:07.763 --> 01:09.069
- It's Wednesday.

01:11.245 --> 01:13.247
What's going on?

01:13.289 --> 01:14.596
Why are you really here?

01:17.033 --> 01:20.210
Can I have a word
with you, please?

01:20.254 --> 01:21.559
- Yeah, you look like
a man on a mission.

01:21.603 --> 01:23.039
What's going on?
- Sean stopped by this morning.

01:23.083 --> 01:24.388
- Mm-hmm.

01:24.432 --> 01:25.781
- To offer me
one of his kidneys.

01:25.824 --> 01:29.001
- Whoa, that's--that's an
incredibly generous gift.

01:29.045 --> 01:30.742
- Yeah, he just decided
to do it out of the blue,

01:30.786 --> 01:31.917
for some reason.

01:31.961 --> 01:33.441
- I just felt like
Sean needed to know

01:33.484 --> 01:34.746
how bad you're actually doing.

01:34.789 --> 01:36.574
- Why,
because he's a blood relative,

01:36.618 --> 01:39.186
and so he might have a shot
at being a match for me?

01:39.229 --> 01:41.188
You put him up to this.

01:41.231 --> 01:42.753
- Offering you a kidney
was all Sean's idea.

01:42.798 --> 01:44.539
- He has not thought
this through, Hannah!

01:44.582 --> 01:46.193
- He has thought
through what it'll be like

01:46.235 --> 01:47.672
to lose his father.

01:47.716 --> 01:49.587
- He doesn't know what it means
to give up a kidney,

01:49.631 --> 01:51.937
and I'm not gonna
let him find out, either!

01:51.981 --> 01:53.287
- Dr. Archer?
- What?

01:53.330 --> 01:54.765
- I'm sorry, uh,

01:54.810 --> 01:56.333
you have a patient waiting
in trauma 2.

01:56.377 --> 01:57.900
- Be right there.

02:00.555 --> 02:03.340
You went to Sean,
against my wishes.

02:03.384 --> 02:04.733
- I wanted to help you.

02:04.776 --> 02:06.213
- You wanna help me?

02:06.256 --> 02:07.475
How about stay out of my life?

02:10.826 --> 02:12.784
- [breathing heavily]
I've been really tired

02:12.828 --> 02:14.308
these past few days,

02:14.351 --> 02:17.528
and I can tell
something's wrong.

02:17.572 --> 02:21.445
Two years ago, I was diagnosed
with myelodysplastic

02:21.489 --> 02:24.100
neoplasm, unclassifiable.

02:24.144 --> 02:27.190
- That's a stem cell disease,
if I'm not mistaken.

02:27.234 --> 02:28.757
Incredibly rare.

02:28.800 --> 02:31.368
- And always
with the threat of turning

02:31.412 --> 02:33.675
into leukemia, unfortunately.

02:35.503 --> 02:38.897
- Kira, show Dr. Archer
the folder.

02:43.511 --> 02:46.209
- Sorry, I must have
left it in the car.

02:46.253 --> 02:48.298
- Kira, I reminded you
three times.

02:48.341 --> 02:49.734
- That's all right, Kimberly.

02:49.778 --> 02:52.128
I've got plenty to work
off of here in your chart.

02:52.172 --> 02:55.827
It says here you've been on
steroids since your diagnosis.

02:55.871 --> 02:58.221
- That's all I can do
to fight the disease.

02:58.265 --> 02:59.831
For now.

02:59.875 --> 03:02.660
Unless a stem cell donor
comes to the rescue.

03:02.704 --> 03:04.184
But I haven't had
much luck with that.

03:04.227 --> 03:07.709
I'm a hard match.

03:07.752 --> 03:08.536
Kira?

03:08.579 --> 03:10.494
[suspenseful music]

03:10.538 --> 03:12.496
Kir--Kira!
- Whoa, whoa, whoa!

03:12.540 --> 03:14.672
Let me get her in another room.

03:14.716 --> 03:17.371
- [panting]

03:21.244 --> 03:23.028
- It's official.

03:23.072 --> 03:25.770
My new house opened escrow.

03:25.814 --> 03:27.511
I feel jittery.

03:27.555 --> 03:29.252
- Well, I mean,
I'd be worried if you didn't.

03:29.296 --> 03:30.819
It's a big deal.

03:30.862 --> 03:32.777
And cause for celebration.
I'm taking you out tonight.

03:32.821 --> 03:35.302
Any restaurant you want,
any restaurant.

03:35.345 --> 03:37.129
- My apartment.

03:37.173 --> 03:38.914
- Oh.
- I'm making golumpki.

03:38.957 --> 03:40.089
Don't ask.

03:40.132 --> 03:41.525
You will love it.

03:41.569 --> 03:43.571
Oh, and my brother's
coming, too--

03:43.614 --> 03:45.050
Pavo.

03:45.094 --> 03:47.139
I was wanting you to meet him.

03:47.183 --> 03:48.140
- Pavo?
- Mm-hmm.

03:48.184 --> 03:50.012
- Golumpki? I'm in.

03:50.055 --> 03:51.970
- Okay.
- 8:00?

03:52.014 --> 03:53.233
- 7:30.
- Okay.

03:53.276 --> 03:54.364
- You help me cook.

03:54.408 --> 03:56.279
- See you there.
- Good.

03:59.761 --> 04:01.328
- Dr. Charles,
do you have a minute?

04:01.371 --> 04:02.764
- Yes.

04:02.807 --> 04:04.940
- My patient in treatment 3
is deaf.

04:04.983 --> 04:07.769
He was clipped by a motorcycle
speeding through a crosswalk.

04:07.812 --> 04:09.553
Banged up a shoulder--
nothing too bad.

04:09.597 --> 04:11.381
- Okay.
- His sister is here with him,

04:11.425 --> 04:13.296
and she asked if they could
see a psychiatrist

04:13.340 --> 04:14.689
as soon as possible.

04:14.732 --> 04:16.298
I asked for a certified
ASL interpreter,

04:16.343 --> 04:17.560
but they're out today
with COVID,

04:17.605 --> 04:19.084
so she's been helping out
on that front.

04:19.128 --> 04:20.303
- Okay.

04:20.346 --> 04:21.826
Thank you.
- Thank you.

04:24.786 --> 04:25.743
[knocking]

04:25.787 --> 04:27.267
- Good morning,
I'm Dr. Charles.

04:29.617 --> 04:32.359
- Hi, uh, I'm Sandy.

04:32.402 --> 04:34.883
And this is my brother, Aiden.

04:34.926 --> 04:37.364
- Nice to, uh,
nice to meet you both.

04:37.407 --> 04:40.062
What's--what's going on?
How can I help?

04:40.105 --> 04:42.325
[suspenseful music]

04:42.369 --> 04:44.196
- That.

04:44.240 --> 04:46.155
That's what's going on.

04:46.198 --> 04:48.462
Aiden's hearing voices.

04:48.505 --> 04:55.643
♪

05:02.606 --> 05:02.824
.

05:02.867 --> 05:05.261
- So Aiden, can you, uh--

05:05.305 --> 05:06.915
can Aiden read lips?

05:06.958 --> 05:08.612
- He's okay. Not great.

05:08.656 --> 05:11.528
It's usually best if I just
interpret through ASL.

05:11.572 --> 05:13.225
- Got it.
- Aiden.

05:13.269 --> 05:15.663
Hey, Aiden, pay attention
to Dr. Charles.

05:15.706 --> 05:18.013
He's here to help you.

05:18.056 --> 05:21.408
- So Aiden, have you--
have you been deaf since birth?

05:23.758 --> 05:26.848
- No, I--

05:26.891 --> 05:30.721
when I was a young kid,
I got sick, and I became deaf.

05:30.765 --> 05:34.551
He had meningitis
as a nine-year-old.

05:34.595 --> 05:35.857
- Got it.

05:35.900 --> 05:37.467
And so these voices that
you've been hearing--

05:37.511 --> 05:39.251
I mean, what are they like?

05:39.295 --> 05:42.994
What kinds of things
are they saying to you?

05:43.038 --> 05:45.040
- Yeah, the voices
that I hear--

05:45.082 --> 05:47.477
they're gentle and kind.

05:47.521 --> 05:50.219
They ask a lot of questions.

05:50.262 --> 05:52.395
They tell me things.

05:52.439 --> 05:55.746
Like today, they told me
to go outside...

05:58.270 --> 06:00.925
Head to Navy Pier...

06:00.969 --> 06:02.362
- [vocalizing]

06:02.405 --> 06:04.538
- And enjoy the sunny day.

06:04.581 --> 06:07.584
- And that's where
the accident happened.

06:11.980 --> 06:16.071
- I was crossing the street,

06:16.114 --> 06:19.466
and I didn't see
a motorbike coming.

06:19.509 --> 06:21.511
- I can certainly
understand how this would be

06:21.555 --> 06:26.690
a very intriguing, even
exciting development for you.

06:26.734 --> 06:28.779
- Yes. Yes.

06:28.823 --> 06:31.260
I can hear again.

06:31.303 --> 06:32.696
- So you know what, Aiden?

06:32.740 --> 06:36.221
I'd like to order some tests
to just determine

06:36.265 --> 06:39.094
if maybe there have been
any neurological changes

06:39.137 --> 06:40.965
that you've undergone recently.

06:41.009 --> 06:42.924
- You think these are
real voices Aiden's hearing?

06:42.967 --> 06:45.753
Asking him questions,
telling him to go to Navy Pier?

06:45.796 --> 06:47.319
- I think it's
important for Aiden

06:47.363 --> 06:50.235
that we rule out any
physiological developments

06:50.279 --> 06:53.021
before we do anything else.

06:53.064 --> 06:55.371
- Fine. Let's run the test.

06:55.415 --> 06:57.808
- I'm just gonna
need his permission.

07:03.423 --> 07:07.339
- Yep. You got him.
- Okay. Great.

07:10.430 --> 07:13.041
- Hi, Kira. I'm Dr. Asher.

07:13.084 --> 07:14.477
How are you feeling?

07:14.521 --> 07:16.957
- Better.
I'm not sure what happened.

07:17.001 --> 07:18.568
- Well, you fainted.

07:18.612 --> 07:22.442
Your blood work showed
that you were dehydrated.

07:22.485 --> 07:26.402
And it also revealed
that you're pregnant.

07:26.446 --> 07:28.491
[apprehensive music]

07:28.535 --> 07:30.667
Did you already
know this, Kira?

07:33.191 --> 07:34.366
- Are you gonna tell my mom?

07:34.409 --> 07:36.020
- No, not if you
don't want me to.

07:36.064 --> 07:37.326
- Please don't.

07:37.369 --> 07:38.849
She won't understand.

07:38.893 --> 07:40.982
- Okay.

07:41.025 --> 07:44.028
Hey, you think maybe
I can do an ultrasound?

07:44.072 --> 07:46.161
So you and I can check out
the fetus together?

07:46.204 --> 07:48.598
Yeah? Okay, great.

07:48.642 --> 07:50.513
I'm just gonna
pull this up, okay?

07:52.384 --> 07:54.822
- I haven't done this part yet.

07:54.865 --> 07:55.909
Kind of nervous.

07:55.953 --> 07:57.259
- Do not worry.

07:57.302 --> 07:58.869
It will not hurt at all,
I promise.

07:58.913 --> 08:00.958
Just might be a little cold
in the beginning.

08:04.440 --> 08:07.138
Okay, here we go.

08:07.182 --> 08:09.184
[ultrasound humming]
All right.

08:09.227 --> 08:12.013
That is the heartbeat.

08:12.056 --> 08:16.887
From its size, it looks
to be about 20 weeks.

08:16.931 --> 08:18.498
- What's wrong?

08:18.541 --> 08:20.238
- Usually, the fetus
and the placenta

08:20.282 --> 08:22.023
are attached to the inside
of the uterus,

08:22.066 --> 08:23.459
but that's not what I'm seeing.

08:23.503 --> 08:25.548
- What are you seeing?

08:25.592 --> 08:27.376
- I am not exactly sure,

08:27.419 --> 08:29.465
so we are going
to send you for an MRI

08:29.509 --> 08:31.554
to get a more precise look.

08:33.034 --> 08:34.861
- This seems really bad.

08:34.905 --> 08:37.908
- All right, let's not get
ahead of ourselves, all right?

08:37.952 --> 08:40.389
And I will be
right here with you.

08:46.874 --> 08:50.225
- So Kira is awake, stable,
and another doctor

08:50.268 --> 08:52.357
is checking on her as we speak.

08:52.401 --> 08:53.881
- It's drugs, isn't it?

08:53.924 --> 08:58.581
She's been so out of it
recently, so secretive.

08:58.625 --> 09:00.670
- We'll know more
about Kira soon.

09:00.714 --> 09:03.368
I do have your results,
however.

09:03.412 --> 09:05.022
- You have a low-grade fever.

09:05.066 --> 09:07.198
Your white blood count is low,

09:07.242 --> 09:09.461
which means your immune system
is weak.

09:09.505 --> 09:12.682
Here on your chest X-ray,

09:12.726 --> 09:14.815
all right, you have these
small infiltrates

09:14.858 --> 09:17.600
in your lungs, which is a sign
that you could have pneumonia.

09:17.644 --> 09:19.602
So I'm gonna start you
on antibiotics, just in case.

09:19.646 --> 09:22.257
- Okay, but I need to know
what's going on with Kira.

09:22.300 --> 09:24.302
You have to tell me something.

09:24.346 --> 09:25.434
Please?

09:25.477 --> 09:27.262
- Okay, just sit tight.

09:27.305 --> 09:28.480
I'll see what I can do.

09:33.355 --> 09:34.661
What's the status
with Kira Ray?

09:34.704 --> 09:36.097
- Still working her up.

09:36.140 --> 09:37.620
- Yeah, well, her mother
would like to be looped in.

09:37.664 --> 09:39.013
- Well, when I have
something to report,

09:39.056 --> 09:40.928
if Kira gives the okay,
I'll share it.

09:40.971 --> 09:43.931
- Oh, so now, you're concerned
about confidentiality, huh?

09:43.974 --> 09:46.107
You do realize that Kira
is a minor and Kimberly

09:46.150 --> 09:48.283
has the legal right to know
her daughter's health status?

09:48.326 --> 09:50.285
- I'm well aware of the issues
surrounding my patient,

09:50.328 --> 09:52.461
whom you are not treating.

09:54.942 --> 09:57.118
- Okay, everyone.
Gravity rounds.

09:57.161 --> 09:59.686
We'll start from the top
and work our way down, okay?

09:59.729 --> 10:03.254
Oh, and let's not forget to
welcome back Dr. Tanaka-Reid.

10:03.298 --> 10:04.647
[applause]

10:04.691 --> 10:05.779
Glad to have you back
on your feet.

10:05.822 --> 10:07.432
- Thank you, Thank you.
- All right.

10:07.476 --> 10:09.347
Let's get it.

10:09.391 --> 10:10.958
[fart noise]

10:11.001 --> 10:12.133
[laughter]

10:12.176 --> 10:13.787
All right, hey.

10:13.830 --> 10:15.397
Everyone get that
out of your systems?

10:15.440 --> 10:17.355
- Oops. Yeah.

10:17.399 --> 10:19.140
[laughs]

10:19.183 --> 10:20.837
- All right, let's go.
Come on.

10:25.712 --> 10:27.801
- Too bad you didn't go
into anesthesia, pal.

10:27.844 --> 10:29.672
'Cause you really know
how to pass gas.

10:31.848 --> 10:33.371
- I'm just saying,
it's not as cut

10:33.415 --> 10:34.982
and dry as you make it sound.

10:35.025 --> 10:36.331
- Well, we're a hospital.

10:36.374 --> 10:37.811
We're entrusted
with saving lives.

10:37.854 --> 10:39.813
I don't see how turning
a profit even comes into it.

10:39.856 --> 10:41.858
- Advanced technology
costs money, Will.

10:41.902 --> 10:44.687
For-profit hospitals are able
to provide better services,

10:44.731 --> 10:46.210
state-of-the-art diagnostics--

10:46.254 --> 10:48.386
- While gouging the average
Joe, who just needs

10:48.430 --> 10:49.692
a chest X-ray
and some antibiotics.

10:49.736 --> 10:51.433
- I'm not saying
it's a panacea, Will.

10:51.476 --> 10:53.043
I'm just saying money is
not the root of all evil.

10:53.087 --> 10:54.828
- It's like I'm dating
Gordon Gekko.

10:54.871 --> 10:57.352
Why do I get the feeling like
I'm sleeping with the enemy?

10:57.395 --> 10:58.875
- I've got surgery to get to.

10:58.919 --> 10:59.963
See you in a bit.

11:01.835 --> 11:03.488
- What about Abe and Ginny?

11:03.532 --> 11:06.491
- Well, they're both
backing Jack.

11:06.535 --> 11:08.537
- To turn Med
into a for-profit hospital?

11:08.580 --> 11:10.017
That's surprising.

11:10.060 --> 11:11.845
- Well, Jack can be
pretty persuasive.

11:11.888 --> 11:14.195
- And he's selling it
as the only way

11:14.238 --> 11:17.459
to keep Med on the cutting edge
of medical advancement.

11:17.502 --> 11:20.070
- Like OR 2.0.

11:20.114 --> 11:22.551
We've got 10 votes for
and 5 against.

11:22.594 --> 11:24.727
Now, Jack needs a 2/3 majority

11:24.771 --> 11:28.557
to abandon our
non-profit status, so...

11:28.600 --> 11:30.037
- It seems
I'm the deciding vote.

11:30.080 --> 11:32.082
- We're hoping we can
count on you, Vernon.

11:32.126 --> 11:33.475
- Yeah.

11:33.518 --> 11:35.042
- I've been proud to sit
on this hospital's

11:35.085 --> 11:36.565
board for 23 years.

11:36.608 --> 11:37.914
As far as I'm concerned,

11:37.958 --> 11:39.742
if it ain't broke,
don't fix it.

11:39.786 --> 11:42.614
Well, maybe if it's
badly sprained.

11:42.658 --> 11:45.356
- Thank you, Vernon.
This is a big relief.

11:45.400 --> 11:46.662
- Yeah, as long as
we won't have

11:46.706 --> 11:48.272
any last-minute defections,

11:48.316 --> 11:51.667
I think we can breathe--easy.

11:51.711 --> 11:53.800
- Are you okay?

11:53.843 --> 11:56.454
- Yeah, yeah, just a headache
I can't seem to shake.

11:56.498 --> 11:58.979
- You look pretty wobbly there,
brother.

11:59.022 --> 12:00.589
- A couple of aspirin,
I'll be fine.

12:00.632 --> 12:02.547
- Oh! Vernon?

12:02.591 --> 12:04.811
- [groans]

12:04.854 --> 12:07.596
I don't know why I got
so dizzy all of a sudden.

12:07.639 --> 12:10.381
[suspenseful music]

12:10.425 --> 12:12.079
♪

12:12.122 --> 12:14.777
- So Aiden's scans
came back, all right?

12:14.821 --> 12:17.693
No sign of a stroke,
nothing on the MRI,

12:17.737 --> 12:19.347
labs came back clean,

12:19.390 --> 12:20.696
all of which suggests--

12:20.740 --> 12:22.785
- He still can't hear anything.
- Correct.

12:22.829 --> 12:25.048
And so at this point,
I have a strong hunch

12:25.092 --> 12:26.702
that what we're
probably looking at

12:26.746 --> 12:29.444
is an early presentation
of schizophrenia

12:29.487 --> 12:31.098
or schizoaffective disorder.

12:31.141 --> 12:32.316
- What do we do?

12:32.360 --> 12:33.578
There's gotta be some sort
of medication

12:33.622 --> 12:35.276
he can take to make
the voices go away.

12:35.319 --> 12:37.408
- There are a lot of options.
It's a treatable disease, okay?

12:37.452 --> 12:38.714
First thing we
need to do, though,

12:38.758 --> 12:39.846
is just to bring Aiden
up to speed.

12:44.981 --> 12:47.636
- Aiden is wondering
why it's a bad thing

12:47.679 --> 12:49.551
for him to hear voices.

12:49.594 --> 12:52.815
- Look, you're hearing things
for the first time in years,

12:52.859 --> 12:54.077
and it's wonderful, right?

12:54.121 --> 12:57.167
These voices,
they're kind, they're gentle.

12:57.211 --> 12:59.648
Problem is, that's very likely
gonna change.

12:59.691 --> 13:01.563
Chances are good
that these voices

13:01.606 --> 13:03.130
could become unpleasant.

13:03.173 --> 13:04.827
They might even ask you
to do something

13:04.871 --> 13:06.524
that could put you
in harm's way.

13:09.005 --> 13:10.398
- Aiden's wondering
if medication

13:10.441 --> 13:11.616
is the best treatment.

13:11.660 --> 13:13.488
- Medication is an
excellent treatment.

13:13.531 --> 13:14.968
Okay, I've had
countless patients

13:15.011 --> 13:17.797
who have been helped
tremendously by medication.

13:23.019 --> 13:25.761
- Will the voices
go away completely?

13:25.805 --> 13:28.155
- You know,
there's no ironclad guarantee.

13:28.198 --> 13:30.287
At the very least,
they will be tamped down,

13:30.331 --> 13:32.768
if not suppressed altogether.

13:35.684 --> 13:38.339
- Then yeah, I want to do that.

13:38.382 --> 13:39.470
Can we start now?

13:39.514 --> 13:41.951
- Absolutely. Yeah.

13:41.995 --> 13:44.214
We can absolutely start now.

13:44.258 --> 13:45.520
Okay.

13:45.563 --> 13:46.956
Well, great.
- Thank you.

13:47.000 --> 13:47.957
- Wonderful.

13:48.001 --> 13:50.003
Well done. It's a big step.

13:50.046 --> 13:53.006
A nurse will be in shortly,
and I'll be back

13:53.049 --> 13:55.225
to check up on you
later in the day, okay?

13:59.708 --> 14:01.014
- So you said you've been

14:01.057 --> 14:02.624
experiencing headaches
recently?

14:02.667 --> 14:05.627
- Uh, off and on
for about ten days.

14:05.670 --> 14:07.585
- Okay, well, Vernon,
I'm inclined to send you

14:07.629 --> 14:08.978
for a head CT, just to be safe,

14:09.022 --> 14:11.851
but in the meantime,
here, follow my finger.

14:13.809 --> 14:15.202
- Morning, Tess.

14:15.245 --> 14:16.899
- Oh, wow.

14:16.943 --> 14:19.380
Who are you looking to impress?

14:19.423 --> 14:20.816
- Impress?
[chuckles]

14:20.860 --> 14:22.339
I had to get
my driver's license renewed.

14:22.383 --> 14:23.688
You know I have to live
with that thing

14:23.732 --> 14:24.864
for, like, five years.

14:24.907 --> 14:26.648
- True. You look fabulous.

14:26.691 --> 14:28.389
- Thank you.
Better go get changed.

14:28.432 --> 14:30.695
- All righty.

14:30.739 --> 14:32.567
[machine beeping]

14:32.610 --> 14:33.785
- Seizing!

14:33.829 --> 14:36.701
2 milligrams of Ativan,
IM, stat.

14:36.745 --> 14:38.312
- It's okay!

14:38.355 --> 14:41.619
Everything's gonna
be all right, Vernon!

14:41.663 --> 14:43.099
Hold on!

14:48.409 --> 14:48.626
.

14:48.670 --> 14:50.585
- I don't understand.

14:50.628 --> 14:52.021
He was fine this morning,
and now you're telling me

14:52.065 --> 14:53.022
he has some kind
of brain tumor?

14:53.066 --> 14:54.632
- A noncancerous tumor.

14:54.676 --> 14:56.634
- "Acoustic neuroma"
is the technical term.

14:56.678 --> 14:58.071
It's most likely
been growing slowly

14:58.114 --> 14:59.333
over the past few months,

14:59.376 --> 15:00.856
compressing
your husband's brain stem

15:00.900 --> 15:02.989
and impacting his hearing
and balance.

15:03.032 --> 15:04.164
- So how do we fix it.?

15:04.207 --> 15:05.643
- I go in and take it out.

15:05.687 --> 15:08.124
- But it is open-brain
surgery, right?

15:08.168 --> 15:09.647
What are the potential risks?

15:09.691 --> 15:11.040
- Well, because of
the tumor's location,

15:11.084 --> 15:12.563
it might be tricky to resect.

15:12.607 --> 15:15.001
There's an elevated risk
of asymmetric paralysis.

15:15.044 --> 15:16.872
- His face?

15:16.916 --> 15:19.744
- Phyllis, Dr. Abrams is the
best neurosurgeon in the city.

15:19.788 --> 15:20.571
- That's true.

15:20.615 --> 15:24.401
[suspenseful music]

15:24.445 --> 15:26.795
- Are there any other options?

15:35.456 --> 15:37.153
- Any updates?
- Not yet.

15:37.197 --> 15:38.807
And I guess
with this development,

15:38.850 --> 15:41.505
the vote's gonna need
to be canceled now.

15:41.549 --> 15:45.379
- [sighs] Jack's looking
to push the agenda as is.

15:45.422 --> 15:47.729
- You're kidding.
- No.

15:47.772 --> 15:50.558
He's eager to come
to a quick resolution

15:50.601 --> 15:53.082
so that everyone
can have an extended break

15:53.126 --> 15:54.562
while Vernon recuperates.

15:54.605 --> 15:57.782
- Yeah, and he can secure
his 2/3 majority.

15:57.826 --> 15:59.306
- Well, Jack didn't
make his fortune

15:59.349 --> 16:01.873
by not taking advantage
of opportunities.

16:01.917 --> 16:03.484
- She's electing
to forgo surgery

16:03.527 --> 16:05.747
and move forward with a
noninvasive radio treatment.

16:05.790 --> 16:08.010
Abrams is hopeful that will
shrink the tumor over time.

16:08.054 --> 16:10.970
- When can he be extubated?
- I don't know.

16:11.013 --> 16:12.928
Even intubated,
we're still having trouble

16:12.972 --> 16:15.409
controlling his seizures.

16:15.452 --> 16:18.673
- [sighs] Well, I'll go
whip the vote again.

16:18.716 --> 16:20.631
See if I can flip someone.

16:22.068 --> 16:23.765
- They're still gonna
have the vote today?

16:23.808 --> 16:26.594
- Don't even concern yourself
with that, Dr. Halstead.

16:26.637 --> 16:31.251
Just see that Vernon gets
the best care possible.

16:31.294 --> 16:33.079
[alarm beeping]

16:33.122 --> 16:34.906
- What do we got?

16:34.950 --> 16:36.604
- 35-year-old Brendan Metz,
took multiple GSWs

16:36.647 --> 16:38.084
stopping a bank robbery.

16:38.127 --> 16:40.347
Hole in right thigh, actively
bleeding when we got him.

16:40.390 --> 16:41.435
- Pressure stable.

16:41.478 --> 16:42.871
Lost about 500 mils of blood

16:42.914 --> 16:44.133
before we got the tourniquet
on him.

16:44.177 --> 16:45.961
Pushed 50 mikes of fentanyl
on the way over.

16:46.005 --> 16:48.746
- Okay, hey, Brendan,
you're at Chicago Med.

16:48.790 --> 16:50.444
We're gonna take
good care of you, okay?

16:50.487 --> 16:51.967
Hang in there for me, bud.

16:54.404 --> 16:56.885
Nice and easy,
on my count, okay?

16:56.928 --> 16:58.278
One, two, three.

16:58.321 --> 17:00.106
- [grunts, groans]

17:00.149 --> 17:02.978
- Thank you, Matt, Juliette.

17:03.022 --> 17:05.633
So Brendan, seems you're
some kind of hero, huh?

17:05.675 --> 17:07.329
- I feel more like
a fool at the moment.

17:07.374 --> 17:10.986
- Well, the world could use
a lot more fools like you.

17:11.030 --> 17:12.335
What are we looking at?

17:12.378 --> 17:14.250
- Hole number one,
right anterior axillary line

17:14.294 --> 17:15.904
at the umbilicus.

17:15.946 --> 17:18.124
Number two, midaxillary line
at the flank at the same level.

17:18.166 --> 17:20.169
- Okay, do they connect?

17:20.213 --> 17:22.911
- Uh, yeah, I think so.

17:22.954 --> 17:23.912
- Let me swab.

17:23.954 --> 17:29.613
♪

17:29.657 --> 17:32.138
Definitely connecting
our superficial.

17:32.181 --> 17:34.270
How about the leg? Thank you.

17:34.314 --> 17:37.665
- Um, two holes here as well.

17:37.708 --> 17:41.538
Number three, mid-medial thigh,
four, lateral mid-thigh.

17:41.582 --> 17:42.844
- No pulses
with a tourniquet up,

17:42.887 --> 17:44.106
so let's go ahead
and loosen that,

17:44.150 --> 17:45.803
see what we're working with.

17:45.847 --> 17:48.806
Type and cross him for 6 and 6,
and push one of each for now.

17:48.850 --> 17:50.547
- [groans]

17:54.377 --> 17:56.162
- Definitely arterial.

17:56.205 --> 17:57.554
It's a hard sign.

17:57.598 --> 17:58.816
Go ahead and retighten
the tourniquet,

17:58.860 --> 18:02.342
and get me X-rays
of the leg and torso.

18:02.385 --> 18:03.778
Come here.

18:05.345 --> 18:06.389
What was that?

18:06.433 --> 18:07.695
Rookie mistake,
putting yourself

18:07.738 --> 18:10.001
in the line of fire like that.

18:10.045 --> 18:12.091
- I guess I'm just
a little off my game.

18:14.180 --> 18:16.834
- All right.
Go get changed and cleaned up.

18:26.235 --> 18:31.806
- Kira, have you ever heard of
the term "ectopic pregnancy"?

18:33.677 --> 18:35.679
It's when a fertilized
egg implants

18:35.723 --> 18:37.594
in the outside of the uterus.

18:37.638 --> 18:39.814
- Is that what's
happening to me?

18:39.857 --> 18:41.163
- Mm-hmm.

18:41.207 --> 18:43.296
Your MRI revealed that
you have a rare type

18:43.339 --> 18:45.080
of an ectopic pregnancy.

18:45.124 --> 18:47.909
It's called
an abdominal pregnancy.

18:47.952 --> 18:50.085
The fetus has attached
to the vena cava,

18:50.129 --> 18:52.479
which is a huge vein
that leads to your heart.

18:52.522 --> 18:54.263
- But the baby's okay, right?

18:54.307 --> 18:55.699
I mean, we saw its heartbeat.

18:55.743 --> 18:57.875
- Yeah, at the moment, it is.

18:57.919 --> 19:01.749
But if the placenta damages
the vena cava for any reason,

19:01.792 --> 19:03.925
that could cause severe
internal bleeding,

19:03.968 --> 19:06.797
which would, in turn,
put your life in jeopardy.

19:06.841 --> 19:08.364
- So what are you saying?

19:08.408 --> 19:11.019
- For your safety,

19:11.062 --> 19:14.457
you need to have surgery
to remove the fetus.

19:14.501 --> 19:16.546
- Will the baby survive?

19:16.590 --> 19:21.421
- At only 20 weeks, no.

19:21.464 --> 19:22.770
I'm so sorry.

19:22.813 --> 19:24.598
- [sobbing]
No. No, you don't understand.

19:24.641 --> 19:26.252
My mom needs this baby.

19:26.295 --> 19:27.775
- What do you mean?

19:27.818 --> 19:29.429
- My mom has
a rare stem cell disease.

19:29.472 --> 19:31.431
It's why we came in today.

19:31.474 --> 19:33.433
She needs a donor, but the
doctors couldn't find one,

19:33.476 --> 19:35.609
and I'm not a match
for her, so--

19:35.652 --> 19:38.568
so I got pregnant.

19:38.612 --> 19:41.223
- Okay, in hopes that
this baby would be

19:41.267 --> 19:43.138
a stem cell match for your mom?

19:43.182 --> 19:44.835
- Yeah.

19:44.879 --> 19:47.795
- Okay, Kira, this is a human
being that we're talking about.

19:47.838 --> 19:49.927
- I know, but I'm gonna raise
the baby,

19:49.971 --> 19:51.451
and I'm gonna be a good mom.

19:51.494 --> 19:53.583
- You're so young, Kira.

19:53.627 --> 19:55.150
Being a mom right now,

19:55.194 --> 19:56.847
your life would never
be the same.

19:56.891 --> 19:59.372
- I can do this, and I want to!

19:59.415 --> 20:02.418
And you know, I always
planned on having kids,

20:02.462 --> 20:03.898
so why not start now?

20:03.941 --> 20:07.162
- Because it's just
too dangerous right now, Kira.

20:07.206 --> 20:09.251
- But what if we waited
a little bit and let the baby

20:09.295 --> 20:11.253
grow a little more
before the surgery?

20:11.297 --> 20:13.429
I mean, would it survive then?

20:13.473 --> 20:19.914
♪

20:19.957 --> 20:21.568
- Hey, you're free, right?

20:23.222 --> 20:26.007
I'd love your eyes
on this acoustic neuroma.

20:26.050 --> 20:27.487
- Hmm.

20:27.530 --> 20:29.010
- You think your mapping tech
could help, you know,

20:29.053 --> 20:30.881
someone like Abrams
confidently resect that?

20:30.925 --> 20:32.492
- Abrams wants
a second opinion from 2.0?

20:32.535 --> 20:34.755
That's hard to believe.

20:34.798 --> 20:36.496
- I'm just doing some
extra legwork for a patient

20:36.539 --> 20:38.106
I'm concerned about.

20:38.149 --> 20:41.544
- Well, let's upload the CT
and MRI and see what they say.

20:43.024 --> 20:45.983
- [yelling]
- Whoa, whoa, whoa!

20:46.027 --> 20:47.898
[alarm beeping]
I know, I know! It's okay!

20:47.942 --> 20:48.856
Aiden!

20:48.899 --> 20:50.205
Stop, please, look at me!

20:50.249 --> 20:51.554
Aiden, Aiden, Aiden!

20:51.598 --> 20:52.990
- What happened?
- I don't know!

20:53.034 --> 20:55.254
- [yelling]

20:55.297 --> 20:56.864
- It's okay, buddy!

20:56.907 --> 20:58.039
What's he saying?
What's he saying?

20:58.082 --> 20:59.606
- I don't know!
- Take it easy, buddy.

20:59.649 --> 21:01.347
- Wait!
- Soft restraints, please!

21:01.390 --> 21:03.871
- [yelling]

21:03.914 --> 21:06.221
- Calm down!
- 5 of Haldol.

21:06.265 --> 21:07.657
- Calm down, Aiden!

21:07.701 --> 21:14.664
♪

21:21.845 --> 21:22.237
.

21:22.281 --> 21:24.500
- Uh, care to
explain your plans

21:24.544 --> 21:26.633
for this abdominal pregnancy?

21:26.676 --> 21:28.243
- Of course
you checked Kira's chart.

21:28.287 --> 21:30.201
- She needs surgery
immediately.

21:30.245 --> 21:31.333
Move her upstairs.

21:31.377 --> 21:33.422
- I'm holding off for now.
- Why?

21:33.466 --> 21:36.120
- Kira wants
to delay the surgery

21:36.164 --> 21:37.426
until the baby is viable.

21:37.470 --> 21:38.601
She hopes that it could be

21:38.645 --> 21:39.733
a stem cell match
for her mother.

21:39.776 --> 21:41.343
- Oh, you're joking.
You're joking.

21:41.387 --> 21:43.084
- It's the reason
Kira got pregnant.

21:43.127 --> 21:44.433
- That is absurd!

21:44.477 --> 21:46.348
And morally repugnant.

21:46.392 --> 21:47.958
She might as well be
organ harvesting.

21:48.002 --> 21:49.873
- She's operating from a place
of care and concern,

21:49.917 --> 21:51.614
not just about her mother,
but for the baby,

21:51.658 --> 21:53.007
and she seems pretty
clear-headed about it.

21:53.050 --> 21:55.618
- That cannot possibly be
what her mother wants.

21:55.662 --> 21:57.359
If you can't convince Kira
to change her mind,

21:57.403 --> 21:58.926
then Kimberly will.

21:58.969 --> 22:01.798
- Kira doesn't want her mother
knowing anything about this.

22:01.842 --> 22:03.800
And she has
medical emancipation

22:03.844 --> 22:05.280
because she's pregnant,

22:05.324 --> 22:07.195
so she can do
anything she wants.

22:16.291 --> 22:18.641
- So good news, Brendan.

22:18.685 --> 22:19.860
The bullet you took
in your side passed

22:19.903 --> 22:21.252
through your love handle.

22:21.296 --> 22:22.993
It's superficial,
and there's nothing more to do.

22:23.037 --> 22:24.386
It'll heal on its own.

22:24.430 --> 22:26.475
Your leg, however...

22:26.519 --> 22:28.259
it's gonna need surgery
emergently, okay?

22:28.303 --> 22:29.783
We're gonna have
to fix the artery,

22:29.826 --> 22:31.741
or you will lose your leg.
- The OR is ready right now.

22:31.785 --> 22:33.656
We just need you to sign
the consent forms,

22:33.700 --> 22:36.398
and we'll bring you up, okay?

22:36.442 --> 22:38.487
- You're in good hands,
all right?

22:38.531 --> 22:40.663
- Is my leg gonna be all right?

22:40.707 --> 22:42.186
- Excuse me?

22:42.230 --> 22:44.014
- Well, I prom--
[groans]

22:44.058 --> 22:45.886
I promised my kid

22:45.929 --> 22:47.540
I'd coach his soccer team
next season.

22:47.583 --> 22:49.280
I'll be able to do that,
won't I?

22:49.324 --> 22:50.804
- We can for sure
fix the artery.

22:50.847 --> 22:52.545
But the nerve runs
right next to it.

22:52.588 --> 22:53.807
We won't know if
you'll have full motor

22:53.850 --> 22:55.156
and sensory function
until after--

22:55.199 --> 22:58.507
- Walk in the park
for us, Brendan.

22:58.551 --> 23:00.553
Don't you fret a lick now,
okay?

23:00.596 --> 23:02.032
- Okay.

23:02.076 --> 23:05.035
[apprehensive music]

23:05.079 --> 23:09.953
♪

23:09.997 --> 23:11.694
- What was that?

23:11.738 --> 23:13.174
- I was just answering
his question.

23:13.217 --> 23:14.610
- No, you were raising
a patient's

23:14.654 --> 23:16.090
stress level unnecessarily.

23:16.133 --> 23:18.309
- He needed to be informed.
Things happen in surgery.

23:18.353 --> 23:20.050
- Why would anything go wrong?

23:20.094 --> 23:21.965
- For any number of reasons.
I don't know.

23:22.009 --> 23:24.533
- Is this about the teasing?

23:24.577 --> 23:27.362
- Is what about the teasing?

23:27.406 --> 23:29.059
- All right, look.

23:29.103 --> 23:30.844
You've been lording over Liam
and the other residents

23:30.887 --> 23:32.280
for almost a year now.

23:32.323 --> 23:34.282
You had to assume they'd
try to knock you down a peg

23:34.325 --> 23:36.284
if they found a vulnerability,
and well,

23:36.327 --> 23:37.328
you gift-wrapped them a doozy.

23:37.372 --> 23:39.548
Whatever. It happened.

23:39.592 --> 23:41.115
Proves you're human.

23:41.158 --> 23:43.247
Laugh it off, and don't
let them get to you.

23:43.291 --> 23:44.901
- I'm not letting them
get to me.

23:44.945 --> 23:46.686
- [sighs]

23:48.514 --> 23:50.254
- Maybe it's best
if I sit this one out.

23:50.298 --> 23:51.734
- I'm sorry.

23:51.778 --> 23:53.606
I don't have the manpower
to spare.

23:59.525 --> 24:01.483
- Sorry to interrupt.

24:01.527 --> 24:03.180
Not sure if you heard,
but Vernon's wife

24:03.224 --> 24:04.921
okayed the craniectomy.

24:04.965 --> 24:07.097
- She's moving forward
with the surgery?

24:07.141 --> 24:10.884
- Dr. Abrams and Song are
prepping OR 2.0 as we speak.

24:10.927 --> 24:13.800
- What got Phyllis
to change her mind?

24:13.843 --> 24:16.672
- Once Dr. Song confirmed 2.0
could reduce much of the risk,

24:16.716 --> 24:19.675
I guess she felt the assurance
she needed to go ahead.

24:19.719 --> 24:20.981
- Wow.

24:21.024 --> 24:22.286
When can we expect
Vernon to come out

24:22.330 --> 24:23.679
from under anesthesia?

24:23.723 --> 24:25.725
- From what I understand,
about three or four hours.

24:25.768 --> 24:26.769
- Ha!

24:26.813 --> 24:28.467
Perhaps I can delay the vote.

24:28.510 --> 24:30.294
At least until Vernon wakes up.

24:30.338 --> 24:32.645
- Good job, Dr. Halstead.
[chuckles]

24:39.652 --> 24:42.045
- Hey, Mags,
if I recall correctly,

24:42.089 --> 24:44.308
you know ASL, right?

24:44.352 --> 24:45.571
- That means yes.

24:45.614 --> 24:47.834
- Okay. What does this mean?

24:51.838 --> 24:55.406
- Something like,
"You take voices away."

24:55.450 --> 24:57.626
- Huh.

24:57.670 --> 24:59.585
You know, I'm treating
a deaf patient,

24:59.628 --> 25:01.674
and his sister's been
interpreting for us.

25:01.717 --> 25:03.676
I'm starting to wonder if--

25:03.719 --> 25:05.504
I don't know--we're getting
our signals crossed

25:05.547 --> 25:06.722
or something like that.

25:09.203 --> 25:10.204
- You want me to spy for you?

25:10.247 --> 25:11.988
- Too strong a word.

25:15.209 --> 25:16.645
How are we doing?

25:16.689 --> 25:20.823
You think it might be time
to get these restraints off?

25:20.867 --> 25:25.001
See if we can maybe figure out
what happened earlier.

25:25.045 --> 25:28.527
- Aiden's calmed down a lot.
- Great.

25:45.065 --> 25:48.677
- Uh, Aiden's upset because
the voices told him the nurses

25:48.721 --> 25:50.723
were gonna make
his shoulder pain worse.

25:50.766 --> 25:52.812
- Um, Aiden, I'm sorry.

25:52.855 --> 25:56.380
Risperidone is typically one of
the faster-acting medications,

25:56.424 --> 25:57.860
but sometimes takes
a little longer.

25:57.904 --> 26:00.907
So how about--how about
we check back in a bit,

26:00.950 --> 26:03.953
and maybe we can
have a chat then?

26:03.997 --> 26:05.520
Okay?

26:05.564 --> 26:09.045
[suspenseful music]

26:09.089 --> 26:15.051
♪

26:15.095 --> 26:17.053
He didn't say anything
about a nurse, did he?

26:17.097 --> 26:18.402
- He's upset because
he can't hear the voices

26:18.446 --> 26:19.708
in his head anymore.

26:19.752 --> 26:21.014
And he suspects
it's because of the pills

26:21.057 --> 26:22.102
that he's been given.

26:22.145 --> 26:23.625
- Yeah, the antipsychotics,

26:23.669 --> 26:25.366
which I dispensed
with his permission.

26:25.409 --> 26:26.715
Or so I was told.

26:26.759 --> 26:28.151
- He thought
it was painkillers,

26:28.195 --> 26:30.240
not antipsychotics.

26:30.284 --> 26:33.069
- Huh.

26:33.113 --> 26:37.030
[alarm blaring]
- [crying, screaming]

26:37.073 --> 26:39.902
- Her BP is dropping,
and her hemoglobin's down to 8.

26:39.946 --> 26:43.123
- Kira?
- It hurts! It hurts!

26:46.213 --> 26:47.910
- Free fluid in the belly,
likely blood.

26:47.954 --> 26:50.086
Kira, we can't hold off
on the surgery any longer.

26:50.130 --> 26:51.653
Call the OR,
tell them to open it stat.

26:51.697 --> 26:53.524
We're bringing Kira up
right away.

26:53.568 --> 26:55.439
- No! Please, no!

26:55.483 --> 27:02.577
♪

27:06.625 --> 27:08.757
- I need to talk to you
about Kira.

27:15.677 --> 27:15.808
.

27:15.851 --> 27:19.550
- I need you for a second.
- Please, no! [sobbing]

27:19.594 --> 27:21.509
- If at any point
during the surgery

27:21.552 --> 27:24.294
you have to make the call
between Kira and the fetus,

27:24.338 --> 27:27.646
please, please,
save my little girl.

27:27.689 --> 27:29.125
- We have every intention
of doing just that.

27:29.169 --> 27:30.823
- We'll have someone keep you
in the loop, Kimberly.

27:32.781 --> 27:34.435
I thought you should
hear that for yourself.

27:34.478 --> 27:35.784
- I cannot believe
you told her.

27:35.828 --> 27:37.264
What about HIPAA?

27:37.307 --> 27:38.700
- Her daughter is heading
into emergency surgery.

27:38.744 --> 27:41.268
If there's a crisis and a
decision needs to be made,

27:41.311 --> 27:43.009
it's Kimberly who'll do it.

27:43.052 --> 27:46.229
[suspenseful music]

27:46.273 --> 27:51.974
♪

27:52.018 --> 27:53.541
- Just came from the pharmacy.

27:53.584 --> 27:55.499
They wouldn't fill Aiden's
prescription for Risperidone?

27:55.543 --> 27:57.719
- Well, I canceled it, Sandy,
because it turns out

27:57.763 --> 28:00.287
it was prescribed without
the permission of the patient.

28:00.330 --> 28:02.115
We should probably have a talk.

28:02.158 --> 28:03.725
- She knows ASL?

28:03.769 --> 28:05.205
- She does.

28:05.248 --> 28:12.386
♪

28:15.084 --> 28:16.651
- What's he saying?

28:16.695 --> 28:19.306
- He's saying that he knows
that she's been lying to him.

28:19.349 --> 28:20.873
- Take the medication.

28:20.916 --> 28:23.658
I was trying to help you.

28:28.489 --> 28:29.969
- But the voices--

28:30.012 --> 28:32.754
they aren't real.

28:32.798 --> 28:34.321
- Aiden says that
he doesn't care

28:34.364 --> 28:36.062
that the voices are not real.

28:36.105 --> 28:37.672
- Sandy, the only way that

28:37.716 --> 28:38.978
we're gonna forge
a path forward--

28:39.021 --> 28:40.631
- I'm not sure there
is a path forward here.

28:40.675 --> 28:43.504
Aiden only cares about hearing
the voices in his head.

28:43.547 --> 28:45.680
And I won't stand by and watch

28:45.724 --> 28:49.510
if you won't do anything
about it.

28:56.299 --> 28:57.692
- Okay, great.

28:57.736 --> 28:59.215
Looks like we have
enough length

28:59.259 --> 29:01.000
to sew the two ends
directly together.

29:01.043 --> 29:02.871
5-0 Prolene stitch.

29:02.915 --> 29:04.264
- I'm sorry, Dr. Marcel?

29:04.307 --> 29:05.700
- What is it?

29:05.744 --> 29:06.962
- I was told to inform you
that there is

29:07.006 --> 29:08.790
an emergent situation
in the OR 2.0

29:08.834 --> 29:11.619
that requires your
immediate attention.

29:11.662 --> 29:13.186
- They're aware I'm in
the middle of surgery?

29:13.229 --> 29:14.535
- They are aware, yes.

29:17.538 --> 29:19.932
- Oh, come on.
All right, everyone.

29:19.975 --> 29:22.369
Dr. Tanaka-Reid will continue
on with the anastomosis

29:22.412 --> 29:24.197
until I return.
Follow his lead.

29:24.240 --> 29:25.589
- We can wait
until you get back.

29:25.633 --> 29:27.809
- No, I don't wanna prolong
his ischemic timing

29:27.853 --> 29:29.071
any more than necessary.

29:29.115 --> 29:31.204
Get the anastomosis done.

29:31.247 --> 29:33.032
I'll be back as soon as I can.

29:33.075 --> 29:37.253
♪

29:37.297 --> 29:38.777
- That's great.
Thank you, Trish.

29:38.820 --> 29:40.735
Go ahead and pull up the feed
in there so I can watch.

29:40.779 --> 29:42.737
- Sure.

29:42.781 --> 29:44.217
All right.

29:44.260 --> 29:46.480
Here goes.
- Awesome. Thank you.

30:00.494 --> 30:04.019
- Trust me, I get
how frustrating it can be

30:04.063 --> 30:05.368
to try and help somebody
who doesn't want it.

30:05.412 --> 30:07.457
- He has no idea
what he's doing.

30:07.501 --> 30:09.242
- You know,
I'm not sure any of us

30:09.285 --> 30:12.419
can really understand what
he's going through right now.

30:12.462 --> 30:14.029
- You must think
I'm a horrible person.

30:14.073 --> 30:15.422
- Do not.

30:15.465 --> 30:17.250
Not at all.

30:17.293 --> 30:19.600
I understand how difficult
it can be for family members

30:19.643 --> 30:20.949
to get this kind of news.

30:20.993 --> 30:22.995
And I completely get
the impulse to just

30:23.038 --> 30:27.086
wanna fix it immediately.

30:27.129 --> 30:32.004
- You know, I had my own issues
with mental illness before.

30:32.047 --> 30:36.965
I know it's not schizophrenia,
but I suffered with depression.

30:37.009 --> 30:38.662
- Really?

30:38.706 --> 30:41.796
- It was especially bad
after our parents died.

30:41.840 --> 30:43.102
Car accident.

30:43.145 --> 30:44.799
Aiden was still
in high school at the time.

30:44.843 --> 30:46.670
- Oh, man.

30:46.714 --> 30:49.456
I can't even imagine.

30:49.499 --> 30:53.068
- Aiden got by somehow.

30:53.112 --> 30:54.940
Maybe it was because
he had already suffered

30:54.983 --> 30:56.680
his own personal tragedy,
losing his hearing,

30:56.724 --> 30:59.335
but he was more resilient.

30:59.379 --> 31:01.903
[sentimental music]

31:01.947 --> 31:04.297
I was such a mess.

31:04.340 --> 31:07.822
My meds saved my life.

31:07.866 --> 31:11.043
I don't know what I would
do without them, honestly.

31:11.086 --> 31:13.654
And I can't stomach
the idea of watching Aiden

31:13.697 --> 31:15.874
go through anything
like what I did.

31:15.917 --> 31:18.877
[crying]

31:20.443 --> 31:22.881
- I get it. I do.

31:26.754 --> 31:30.323
Have you ever told Aiden
about any of this stuff?

31:30.366 --> 31:32.194
- The last thing
I'd ever wanna do

31:32.238 --> 31:33.500
is burden Aiden
with my problems.

31:33.543 --> 31:35.458
He doesn't need that.

31:35.502 --> 31:37.025
- I think you might
be surprised by what

31:37.069 --> 31:38.722
he's capable of handling.

31:38.766 --> 31:40.507
You know, people who learn
to manage this disease,

31:40.550 --> 31:43.945
I mean, they live
full, productive lives.

31:43.989 --> 31:45.686
I mean, they can, really.

31:45.729 --> 31:48.863
You know, listen,
outcomes improve significantly

31:48.907 --> 31:51.561
when loving family members
stay involved.

31:51.605 --> 31:53.520
So you know,
he's gonna be relying on you,

31:53.563 --> 31:54.913
especially at first.

31:54.956 --> 31:57.872
But with a little luck,
sooner rather than later,

31:57.916 --> 32:02.007
he's probably gonna be able
to return that favor.

32:02.050 --> 32:07.012
And, um, how wonderful
would that be?

32:07.055 --> 32:11.668
♪

32:18.284 --> 32:20.677
- Vernon should be out
of surgery any minute now.

32:23.028 --> 32:25.987
- Strange how Phyllis
changed her mind.

32:26.031 --> 32:27.989
- Happens pretty frequently,
actually.

32:28.033 --> 32:30.122
A big decision like that,

32:30.165 --> 32:32.254
sometimes people need
a little time to process.

32:32.298 --> 32:35.257
[tense music]

32:35.301 --> 32:38.957
♪

32:39.000 --> 32:40.262
- So how'd it go?

32:40.306 --> 32:41.960
- Fairly certain we got
a complete resection.

32:42.003 --> 32:43.570
No problem with the margins,
as far as I can tell.

32:43.613 --> 32:45.659
Electrophysiology
looked perfect.

32:45.702 --> 32:47.139
- But you don't know
for sure yet, right?

32:47.182 --> 32:49.097
So how long exactly
until he wakes up?

32:49.141 --> 32:50.490
- I'm a brain surgeon, Jack.

32:50.533 --> 32:53.623
Not a soothsayer.

32:53.667 --> 32:55.669
- Is it gonna be today?
- What can I say, Jack?

32:55.712 --> 32:57.932
When he's ready to be
extubated, he will be.

32:57.976 --> 33:02.545
♪

33:02.589 --> 33:05.809
Jack seems awfully interested
in Vernon's recovery time.

33:05.853 --> 33:07.768
- Pretty sure it's about
the board meeting later.

33:07.811 --> 33:09.335
He's probably sweating
now that Vernon might

33:09.378 --> 33:11.250
be able to vote against him.

33:11.293 --> 33:13.034
- Vernon's the deciding vote?

33:13.078 --> 33:14.993
- That's what I hear.

33:15.036 --> 33:17.169
- Were you aware of that when
you urged me to get involved?

33:19.780 --> 33:21.608
I heard rumors of you
acting like a cowboy.

33:21.651 --> 33:23.784
- That's not
what happened today.

33:23.827 --> 33:25.612
I came here out of concern
for the patient.

33:25.655 --> 33:26.917
- Who are you trying
to convince with that?

33:26.961 --> 33:28.049
Me or you?

33:28.093 --> 33:35.013
♪

33:39.669 --> 33:39.887
.

33:39.930 --> 33:42.324
- Well, your facial
movement's symmetrical,

33:42.368 --> 33:44.457
and your hearing
appears to be intact.

33:44.500 --> 33:47.547
- What a relief.
Thank you all.

33:47.590 --> 33:50.071
- Well, I understand
a celebration is in order.

33:50.115 --> 33:51.290
- It appears so.

33:51.333 --> 33:53.727
My apologies to everyone
for the scare.

33:53.770 --> 33:55.903
- The board is gonna be
excited to hear the news.

33:55.946 --> 34:00.168
Speaking of,
the meeting's about to start.

34:00.212 --> 34:01.691
Look, Vernon, no one
would question you

34:01.735 --> 34:03.389
if you opted
to sit this one out.

34:03.432 --> 34:05.086
- Well, I certainly don't
feel like I'm ready

34:05.130 --> 34:08.263
to get out of bed, but I wonder
if it'd be possible

34:08.306 --> 34:10.178
for me to video-conference in.

34:10.222 --> 34:14.443
- Of course,
we can make that happen.

34:14.487 --> 34:15.661
- Great.

34:15.705 --> 34:16.837
Well, I'll see you then.

34:25.150 --> 34:27.108
[beeping]

34:27.152 --> 34:29.067
- Triphasic signals.

34:29.110 --> 34:30.284
- Well, is that good?

34:30.329 --> 34:31.591
- Pulse is strong.

34:31.634 --> 34:33.288
Exactly what
we were hoping for.

34:33.331 --> 34:35.116
In a few weeks,
you can start getting ready

34:35.159 --> 34:36.770
for soccer season.

34:36.813 --> 34:37.858
- Man, thank you.

34:37.900 --> 34:38.946
Thank you both.

34:38.989 --> 34:39.902
- You bet.

34:42.775 --> 34:44.342
Nice job, by the way.

34:44.386 --> 34:46.822
- Like you said,
I could handle it on my own.

34:46.867 --> 34:48.956
- Indeed.

34:48.998 --> 34:50.262
- I checked the board
when I got out of surgery

34:50.304 --> 34:51.480
and noticed that
Abrams was using

34:51.524 --> 34:53.395
the OR 2.0 this afternoon.

34:53.438 --> 34:56.137
No record of you
stepping in at all.

34:56.181 --> 34:57.617
- Yeah.

34:57.660 --> 34:59.271
Wires must have gotten
crossed somewhere.

34:59.314 --> 35:01.621
It was actually Onc Surg
that needed a hand.

35:01.664 --> 35:04.798
- I know you're
probably lying to me.

35:04.841 --> 35:06.974
But I'm appreciative
nonetheless.

35:07.017 --> 35:10.934
[sentimental music]

35:10.978 --> 35:12.675
- It'll be okay.
- Kira!

35:12.719 --> 35:15.461
- Mom?

35:15.504 --> 35:17.637
- Is she gonna be okay?
- Yes.

35:17.680 --> 35:19.204
She has some recovery time
ahead of her,

35:19.247 --> 35:21.119
but she'll be okay.

35:21.162 --> 35:25.166
Unfortunately, we were not able
to save the fetus.

35:25.210 --> 35:26.820
- I'm so sorry, Mom.

35:26.863 --> 35:30.215
- Oh, Kira, honey,
what were you thinking?

35:30.258 --> 35:31.651
- You need a stem cell donor.

35:31.694 --> 35:34.480
I thought that maybe
if I had a baby, then--

35:34.523 --> 35:36.395
- Look at me, honey.

35:36.438 --> 35:38.527
I'm gonna be--

35:38.571 --> 35:42.227
we're gonna get through this.

35:42.270 --> 35:44.142
We haven't found a donor yet,

35:44.185 --> 35:46.231
but these things,
they take time.

35:46.274 --> 35:49.190
- What if we can't?

35:49.234 --> 35:52.193
- We just have to be brave.

35:52.237 --> 35:54.891
I know that
won't be hard for you.

35:54.935 --> 35:57.764
- We're gonna give you
some privacy.

36:02.943 --> 36:05.206
- Boy, is she lucky.
- Oh, absolutely.

36:05.250 --> 36:06.381
Kira could have died today.

36:06.425 --> 36:08.862
- I'm talking about Kimberly.

36:08.905 --> 36:11.473
How unbelievably lucky
she is to have a daughter

36:11.517 --> 36:13.736
willing to make such
a generous act of love.

36:13.780 --> 36:20.874
♪

36:21.483 --> 36:24.007
- How are Aiden
and Sandy doing?

36:24.051 --> 36:27.272
- Yeah, it looks like
they're working it out.

36:29.056 --> 36:31.667
- Aw, looks like they made up.

36:31.711 --> 36:33.365
- Yeah.

36:33.408 --> 36:36.455
Nothing like coming clean
to re-establish trust.

36:42.678 --> 36:43.679
- Hey.

36:46.291 --> 36:48.249
Can we talk?

36:48.293 --> 36:51.034
- Yeah.
- Yeah?

36:51.078 --> 36:53.254
All right. Uh...

36:55.691 --> 36:58.738
This morning, your offer--

36:58.781 --> 37:02.045
you realize what this
could mean, right?

37:02.089 --> 37:04.396
If you have some sort
of health crisis someday

37:04.439 --> 37:05.571
with only one kidney left--

37:05.614 --> 37:08.487
- I know what I'm risking.

37:08.530 --> 37:10.053
- You do not have to do this.

37:10.097 --> 37:12.099
- Dad, you don't understand.

37:12.142 --> 37:13.535
I need to do this.

37:17.974 --> 37:21.108
- If you turn out
to be a match, uh,

37:21.151 --> 37:23.328
I won't say no.

37:23.371 --> 37:30.160
♪

37:30.204 --> 37:33.512
both:
Na zdrowie.

37:33.555 --> 37:36.166
- And golumpki?

37:36.210 --> 37:37.342
Oh, my gosh, delicious.

37:37.385 --> 37:38.560
- Thank you.

37:38.604 --> 37:40.301
- Liliana is a wonderful cook.

37:40.345 --> 37:41.520
And you know what?

37:41.563 --> 37:43.348
She can clean.

37:43.391 --> 37:44.436
A professional.

37:44.479 --> 37:45.524
You don't need a maid now.

37:45.567 --> 37:47.352
- Pavo.
- What?

37:47.395 --> 37:49.267
It was a joke!

37:49.310 --> 37:50.311
Here.

37:50.355 --> 37:51.443
- No, I'm good.

37:51.486 --> 37:53.314
Thank you very much.
It's delicious.

37:53.358 --> 37:54.924
I gotta drive, gotta drive.

37:54.968 --> 37:56.143
- Oh, good!

37:56.186 --> 37:58.014
Responsible.

38:00.669 --> 38:01.975
So.

38:02.018 --> 38:03.585
Pan Daniel.

38:03.629 --> 38:04.934
- Pan?Pan Daniel?

38:04.978 --> 38:07.154
- It means "sir."

38:07.197 --> 38:10.157
- You are an important man
with an important job.

38:10.200 --> 38:11.332
- Oh, I don't know about that.

38:11.376 --> 38:15.336
Um, can't imagine
doing anything else.

38:15.380 --> 38:17.338
Certainly keeps me on my toes.

38:17.382 --> 38:20.341
- A lucky man who
doesn't hate his job.

38:20.385 --> 38:22.691
- Say that again. Lucky indeed.

38:24.650 --> 38:27.348
- So tell me, Doctor.

38:27.392 --> 38:29.176
You deal with any
crazy people today?

38:29.219 --> 38:30.743
- You know what, Pavo?
Even if I wanted to,

38:30.786 --> 38:32.135
I wouldn't be able to tell you.

38:32.179 --> 38:33.833
And honestly,
I don't love that word.

38:33.876 --> 38:35.835
I don't know,
maybe it's a shrink thing.

38:35.878 --> 38:37.010
Anyway.

38:37.053 --> 38:39.665
- I'm sorry.
My English is not so good.

38:39.708 --> 38:41.971
- It's okay.
- Not so correct.

38:42.015 --> 38:43.451
I didn't mean to offend.

38:43.495 --> 38:45.975
- None taken, whatsoever.

38:46.019 --> 38:47.455
- But you must have
some good stories.

38:47.499 --> 38:49.849
- Pavo!
- What?

38:49.892 --> 38:51.372
He doesn't want
to talk about his work.

38:51.416 --> 38:52.982
I get it.

38:53.026 --> 38:54.680
- I think I'm going to check
on the babka.

38:54.723 --> 38:57.247
- And I'm gonna get rid
of some of these dishes.

38:57.291 --> 39:00.250
[both speaking Polish]

39:00.294 --> 39:03.036
[tense music]

39:03.079 --> 39:09.956
♪

39:09.999 --> 39:12.437
- What did he, uh--
what did he say?

39:12.480 --> 39:14.047
- Oh, he was, uh--

39:14.090 --> 39:17.442
he was just wondering
if we had any more vodka.

39:17.485 --> 39:24.579
♪

39:27.277 --> 39:28.540
- Hey, Sharon.

39:28.583 --> 39:29.715
Do you have a minute?

39:29.758 --> 39:31.325
- Oh, is it important, Maggie?

39:31.369 --> 39:33.066
This is really not a good time.

39:33.109 --> 39:34.676
- It kind of is.

39:34.720 --> 39:37.200
- Okay, come. Come here.

39:37.244 --> 39:38.637
What's up?

39:38.680 --> 39:41.422
- I lied to you earlier,
and I feel horrible about it.

39:41.466 --> 39:43.424
- Lied? About what?

39:43.468 --> 39:46.471
- I didn't get all dressed up
to renew my driver's license.

39:46.514 --> 39:48.690
I was meeting
with a headhunter.

39:48.734 --> 39:50.997
About maybe finding
another job.

39:51.040 --> 39:52.738
- Okay.

39:52.781 --> 39:55.915
- I was frustrated
last week in ED, and I--

39:55.958 --> 39:57.569
I called them.

39:57.612 --> 40:00.572
I instantly regretted it,
and I feel guilty

40:00.615 --> 40:03.357
even thinking about leaving.

40:03.401 --> 40:06.099
With all the changes that are
going down in the ED

40:06.142 --> 40:09.058
and all this chatter
about going for-profit...

40:10.930 --> 40:12.453
I have a bad feeling
about the direction

40:12.497 --> 40:14.063
that Jack is taking us.

40:14.107 --> 40:15.804
- I get your frustration,
Maggie,

40:15.848 --> 40:17.850
and I promise you,
we're working

40:17.893 --> 40:20.418
on a course correction
as we speak.

40:20.461 --> 40:23.725
The board is in the process
of defeating Jack's agenda,

40:23.769 --> 40:26.162
and we're going
to hold the line.

40:26.206 --> 40:28.251
- Good.

40:28.295 --> 40:29.514
I really don't wanna leave Med.

40:29.557 --> 40:34.301
♪

40:34.344 --> 40:36.390
- It's a great day
for Gaffney, everybody.

40:36.434 --> 40:38.131
- Thank you.

40:38.174 --> 40:40.133
- I'm gonna make sure to have
an even brighter future.

40:40.176 --> 40:42.483
- Thank you.

40:42.527 --> 40:45.312
- George? What's going on?

40:45.355 --> 40:48.446
- [sighs] Jack.

40:48.489 --> 40:50.665
He got the votes.

40:50.709 --> 40:54.147
We are now
a for-profit hospital.

40:54.190 --> 40:55.322
- How?

40:55.365 --> 40:56.454
Who flipped?

40:56.497 --> 40:57.846
- Vernon!

40:57.890 --> 41:00.153
Apparently, he was
so impressed with 2.0,

41:00.196 --> 41:03.504
he decided to be supportive
of any measure

41:03.548 --> 41:05.158
that would bring in
more advancement

41:05.201 --> 41:07.813
in high-tech medicine.

41:07.856 --> 41:10.468
Sharon, I am so sorry.

